Epic orders from history #1: In 46BC, Julius Caesar ordered two extra days be added to August. Changing it up from 29 to 31 days was just one fix he made to the wonky Roman calendar year that until then had no fixed length. So two thumbs up, Julius, for helping us know exactly when next payday will roll around. Join us for a takeaway to say thanks?

This update makes it easier for you to place your own epic order by showing you when restaurants will be busiest, letting you beat the rush and get your order in ahead of the rest.

We’ve also fixed a small bug that was causing the Menulog help centre to not display correctly on iPhone X.

Epic orders from history #2: If you’ve ever fancied eating a balloon, there’s a restaurant in Chicago, USA, where you can order one for dessert. An apple and sugar mixture is inflated with voice-changing helium, which means you’ll sound as silly as you look when you eat it. At a wallet-deflating $190 a pop though, it’s quite possibly just a lot of hot air.

This month’s update includes the usual ingenious ingredients that make ordering the food you love easier than ever.

Epic orders from history #3: Fuelled by grilled cheese sandwiches (his favourite), President Franklin D. Roosevelt rescued the USA from the Great Depression in the 1930s. He did so, in part, by issuing a whopping 3,522 executive orders – more than ten times the average number of orders from any other president, before or since.

Features fresh from the grill this month include:

Order it again
We know lots of you love to re-order your favourite foods from your favourite restaurants. To make it even easier, a handy new Order it again selection has been added to the home screen. Get stuck in.

Re-designed home screen
We’ve re-designed the home screen to make it a bit more friendly and personal to you.

Improved restaurant search
Grab the grub you love with our new search filters and cuisine picker.

Potatoes on a plane? Thanks to their chemical makeup and high water content, potatoes absorb Wi-Fi frequencies much like human bodies do. It is so similar that some airlines have taken to seating sacks of potatoes to test their on-board wireless signal.

This month’s updates that’ll help you more easily absorb some potatoes (or whatever else you would like) include:

Popular cuisines
Now it's easier to find restaurants serving your favourite cuisines thanks to new cuisine short-cuts on the home screen.

Planning a dinner party for the ages? Cleopatra had a few ideas. To win a bet with Marc Antony that she could throw the world’s most lavish feast, legend has it that Cleo had crushed pearls added to the wine she was serving. A glass of which, some clever clogs reckon, would cost a cool half-million in today’s money.

The pearls of this month include a few small improvements to the performance of our app.

Like a little spice in your curry, we’ve made a few upgrades that’ll make your app experience better than ever:

• Menulog is part of the Just Eat family. We've tweaked our logo to show that we're one big team.
• Like our delivery drivers, we’ve got a need for speed – we’ve streamlined our Customer Service Team so now you can get an answer to your queries even faster.
• Forget your password? We’ve got your back. Our forgotten password link is back up and running.
• Say hello to universal links. Now you can get automatically redirected to our app if you click on any link that leads to Just Eat.

Like a spicy bolognese with a few secret ingredients, our app's had a few upgrades:

We’ve improved how we support the pictures on our app, so now you’ll always see your favourite dishes when you search for what you want.

We've fixed a couple of bugs to keep everything running nice smooth.

What does your food get up to before it arrives at your place? We’ve been taking a look at your delivery tracking experience. Here's what we've been doing:

• Removing the driver icon from the map when your food’s arrived
• Refreshing the style of the icons, so now they’re style icons, and they’re lookin’ goooood

We’ve also sorted out the ‘session timeout’ message so it’s a bit more clear, just in case your basket gets emptied because you can’t decide which tasty takeaway you want to order.
